segments.text: your colleagues when you got here?
Who were they and what were their specialties and so forth?
Before I do that, there's one more thing I thought of that Jack Williams said that evening that I've not forgotten.
One, and I don't recall, this is not a direct quote, but it's fairly close.
He said, right as his closing comments, he said, I hope that you're all welcome here.
We're pleased that you came our way.
You'll make us better for having been here.
But I hope each of you, like young people,
And I hope that you think they are our best hope for the future.
And if you don't, I hope your stay here is very, very short.
And I remember that and have used that many times along the way.
In our department when I got here was a guy named Linus Dow.
And Linus was a biomechanics type person.
He studied the angles of bouncing balls and muscle joints and those kind of things, the most efficient way to do an activity.
course Carl Landis was the department head.
Carl had gotten his degree at Penn State and Landis had gotten his degree at Missouri.
There's a guy named Jack Chivret who was a Canadian who did his undergraduate work in Springfield College which was the very first

program in physical education where basketball was that's right that's right and he he had gotten his doctorate from florida state he ran he did the student teaching program and did that very well he was very organized and detailed and and took care of things well emil mamaluga who was the director of the act what we call the activity program then the the program where they taught
taught different sports skills like golf and tennis and racquetball and so forth.
Leslie Palmer was the admiral director.
We had an adjunct whose name was Dr. Bill Roman, no BGYN in town, who taught a human diseases course.
Mildred Little had come in with me and she was an outdoor education type person.
Homer Tolson, testing measurements, statistics.
He came from Purdue.
One of the very best teachers I've ever seen, and certainly one of the best I've seen in that particular field.
Robert Hurley was my colleague in health education and had a degree from Utah, University of Utah.
And George Jessup.
who was in exercise physiology and he came from the University of Southern California.
And every one of those guys and gals are now retired, which gave me my first clue that it was time for me to retire.
Also, they seem to me to be geographically diverse.
Very diverse faculty.
We had, I see, I guess had a degree from A&M and Les Palmer did.
And they were the only ones with local degrees.
And everyone else was spread out.
Dow from Missouri, Landis from Penn State, Florida State, Mildred Little from the University of Texas, Tolson, Purdue, Hurley, Utah, I was from Tennessee, and Jessup from USC.
So it was an eclectic group.
As far as you can recall, what were your first course assignments?
I came here to direct the Allied Health Program.
And so my first year I was 75% time on that grant.
Okay.
The next year I was 50% time.
The following year I was 25% time and then I was 100%.
So my first teaching assignment was to teach an undergraduate class
methodology, methods of teaching health.
And for the first time, I taught that course before, but as I said earlier, at Southeastern, we taught 15 hours a semester and you just hardly could do anything except go to school and write papers.
For the first time, I had a chance to
really planned for that class and I thought I got pretty good at it.
I also taught a graduate course called Health Careers which no longer exists and for good reason.
Now this first course was for upper-class?
It was a capstone course for our graduating seniors.
Describe your first impression of Aggie students.
Well I had mostly men
I think there was three girls, three or four girls in that class, and it was a large class, about 40 in there.
Nearly all of them wore boots.
All of them were in uniform, except there were a handful of men who were not in uniform and, of course, none of the women.
They were...
They were good students.
I was singularly impressed with that.
Of course, the school where I was in southeast Louisiana didn't draw the very best of students than it was anyway, so that was a step up from that point of view.
But they were good kids.
They were well-behaved.
If you called on them, they would give you an at you.
But if you didn't call on them, they weren't going to volunteer anything.
Very polite.
Attended.
You didn't have to worry about whether they were going to be in school or not.
They came?
They came to class.
In that era, did you check the roll?
I did check the roll.
I did it for a reason entirely different than attendance, though.
Until several years later, I tried to learn every student's name.
And by the end of the first three or four weeks, if I called roll every day, I would have it.
And these students, as far as you could tell, where were they from and what was their basic philosophical outlook on life?
It had a definite rural blend to it.
Like now, there were some students from Houston and some from Dallas, but most of them were regional kids from Brenham and Hearn and Snook and places like that.
A lot of them, looking back, I didn't think about it then because it didn't seem unreasonable to me, but looking back, are unusual to me.
Looking back, I...
I think most of them were first-generation college kids, and pretty much in awe of the university.
Their philosophy was, let me get in, get this done, and get out.
I have to go to work.
Were most of them majors in the department?
Yeah, all of these would be majors, because it was a capstone.
And as far as you could tell, what was their career goal?
They were all going to be teachers or coaches.
At that time, that's the only option we had in our program.
And how did they introduce you to any Aggie ways of doing things or excuses or pranks?
Oh, I learned more stuff that year than I would ever learn.
Share some of it.
Well, believe it or not, I had never heard an Aggie joke until I came on this campus.
All the Aggie jokes I heard were here.
And one of the things I had learned pretty quick as I moved out, I spent that first year in Austin a lot because I was developing this allied health program and putting together brochures and things.
And I was moving around the state trying to meet some of the schools where that was being taught.
And everywhere I'd go, people would be delighted to tell me an Aggie joke.
So I put a few pro-Aggie jokes in my arsenal to use along the way.
Of course, the walk, I'd never heard of the walk before.
They tried to introduce that to me very quickly.
We need a walk on Friday.
I'll never forget the first elephant walk.
I thought we were being marched on by, this was 72, and they were still marching in some campus.
I thought they were
They were about to march on the president's office.
CT, that term came up, and I had the ignorance of asking what that meant in class.
And a lot of red faces, and one kid said, Dr. Ponder, I'll tell you after class.
But they all giggle about that.
Do you remember any, in that first year or so, any pranks or jokes on you that they attempted?
No, they didn't.
I always had the kind of demeanor, I think, that kept a glass wall someplace.
Someone taught me that pretty early.
But I remember wearing an orange tie to class one day.
I had to go home and dig all that stuff out, because coming out of Tennessee, I had some orange things.
Did someone say anything?
Oh, yes.
They said, we don't like your tie.
And I said, well, I normally let my wife dress me.
I thought it went all right.
She said, it's not that.
We don't like the color of your tie.
I said, well, it matches all right.
No, it doesn't match A&M at all.
That's a good one.
Let's see.
You were there pretty well all day.
Did Dr. Landis practice himself the expectations he had?
Oh yes.
No question about that.
He was there early and he left late.
And how did he keep the department pooled together?
Did you all have regular meetings?
We had regular meetings.
At that time, we could all meet in a room smaller than this one.
But we would have regular faculty meetings.
And of course, he used memos with great regularity.
We had a meeting place like all the departments had then.
We had a coffee room and a mail room.
It was kind of common practice around 10 o'clock, if you didn't have a class, you wandered down and checked your mail.
And there were a lot of impromptu meetings would occur right there around a coffee pot.
And so, by and large, you all had coffee in the department?
Yes, we did.
And then where did you and your closest colleagues go eat lunch?
Across the street, MSC was right across the street from us, so a lot of people would go over there.
I would go home often.
It wasn't that hard of a drive.
Even though it was quite a piece of way, I could make it in about seven minutes.
I had, I think, two lights between me and the house.
And you parked?
I parked right by my building, walked right to it.
Was there even a parking fee?
There was no parking fee.
I thought I didn't remember one at that time.
We had a bumper sticker, but no parking fee.
In terms of how did you and your wife, how did you all become part of the community?
That was no problem at all.
This, as you know, is an unusual community.
We were told when we got here that we'd be busy.
And we looked around and saw a sleepy little town.
And how could that be?
And we realized early on that you had to learn to say no because there were just so many opportunities that came your way.
But what really impressed us was we came from, Southeastern is a strong Italian town.
Granted, some Cajun in that area, but mostly Italians.
And they're very slow to take you in, and really good people.
Once they adopt you, you're adopted.
But we didn't have that problem here.
Even the grocery stores, folks were friendly.
And I still hear that.
When we get a new faculty who comes in for an interview, they still remark about how friendly people are.
So we were absorbed.
It was almost like we had always lived here.
One thing that helped us was there was a guy named Walter Penberthy, which we call Penny.
Penny's wife and my wife's mother were good friends.
One of my wife's mother's good friends had gone to school with Lollibeth.
And so we knew them almost instantly.
And when we came for an interview, we were told to look them up.
But we didn't.
We didn't know them from anyone else.
But after we got here and we settled and knew them, well,
really worked us over for not having come by our house.
But they instantly introduced us to their circle of friends.
And the department had several social kinds of things during the year.
Yeah, describe those.
Well, we had an ice cream social to begin the year.
Everybody could turn a half gallon of ice cream.
And we had cookies and ice cream.
We had a golf tournament in the early part of the year and at the end of the year.
They had what they called the fin and feather tournament, where the fin was fishing and feather was birdies for golf.
And we did those kinds of activities.
And then having a watering hole in the department helped an awful lot.
It was an easy matriculation from that point of view.
Did you all join any organizations off campus, churches, anything?
Well, we were.
Of course, we're Baptists, so we very quickly joined the First Baptist Church in Bryan, and that's instant family and friends.
I tried my hand at the Qantas Club for a short time.
I joined a breakfast club, but gosh, those guys eat early in the morning.
Trying to get up and get to that and then get to work was more than I could do.
And the wives got together quite often.
They had what they called the nitwits, which they would get together and knit.
The faculty wives in the department.
So that should be spelled K-N-I-T. That's right.
And those girls are still real close friends.
Some of them moved as far away as Colorado, and they still keep up with one another.
Let me turn this off a second.
That first fall,
Did you and your wife ever talk about whether or not you, that this was a good place to be?
Oh, yeah.
We, I bet we weren't here two weeks.
And I came in one day and said, I'm going back to Southeastern.
I just don't fit in here.
Health really wasn't a high priority in Carl's mind.
He was a physical educator and that's what he was pushing.
I didn't see that changing real soon.
And I had a real good situation back there.
And, of course, my wife didn't want to do that at all.
She liked it here.
She instantly liked it.
And we talked about it.
Had she been willing to go, I probably, at the end of that year, would have gone.
And that would have been the biggest mistake that I'd ever made at any time.
All right.
Then what led you to change that?
One of the big things was that...
at dinner that we talked about.
That really made a big difference.
But as I got to know Carl better, and as he got to know me better, I came to realize he just wanted good programs.
He wasn't going to line up and try to develop health.
That wasn't his field.
But he had had a long line of folks in that area that had not done very good work.
And as that got better, I looked at the university differently.

And then I got to know, oh, one of the social clubs I joined, I'm an avid golfer, you probably know that, I joined Blackrest, and I got to know a lot of the guys over there, a lot of the guys in vet medicine.
Roy England and Fred Heck and, I mean, just Mike Tatum, just a whole host of them.
And I never met anybody from that field that weren't just 100% solid people.
And that added to it.
But I guess the biggest thing was the fact that
But I got the feeling that I could fit in here and it would work.
Describe how you developed your plans for the health education program and then how they came to become reality.
Two things were happening.
The allied health program that I was in charge of, the idea behind it was that we needed more allied health people like medical technologists and dental hygienists and physical therapists.
But there weren't enough schools to train them.
And people who were in those fields wanted to be doing that kind of work and not teaching because it scared them to get out of the doing.
They'd lose their skills.
And our role was to identify folks who were out in the practice, convince them to come back and get a master's degree or a doctoral degree so they then could take faculty jobs.
And early on, that wasn't going well.
I'd go and talk to people, and they'd say, well, good luck.
But there weren't many takers then.
When I came on board, Carl had identified six or eight folks who were going to be there in September, and none of them showed up.
We finally, toward the end of the year, we got one person in who was not a strong student.
He was a good student, but it was not a good match.
It worked out all right, but it was a difficult one.
And it took a while to get that going.
and primarily it involved building brochures and mail outs and going to professional meetings
and visiting and shaking hands and talking and I guess somewhere around the end of that first year, I began to see, I thought it wasn't gonna happen, it began to happen.
And then we got a federal grant which paid for some scholarships, some fellowships actually for those folks and that really got it going.
Did you write that proposal?
I wrote that proposal and in fact hand delivered it up to Washington, which was another thing that impressed me about A&M.
I got a lot of help in doing that.
There was a lot of offices, as you know, on campus where people could help you build budgets, and here are some things you shouldn't put in here, and here are things you should put in.
And like all those deadlines, they were real tight.
And I came down to the wire, and they said, well, jump on a plane and take it up there.
And that's what I did.
And not many people got those grants.
We were one of, I think, five institutions that got them.
How many students did that?
That supported...
three doctoral students, and five master's students for about five years.
And so they began to arrive in the fall of?
Oh, let's see, this would be 72, 82, probably 83 is when they started arriving.
You say 80?
No, no, 70.
I came in 72.
72 was a dry year.
73, I saw a little 74.
Yeah.
1974, I started seeing them come in in great numbers.
And we had a nucleus of people.
And then it was a matter of just writing a letter and responding and treating people like human beings.
And we had it going.
As you look back, were some of those first students real key people?
We had one guy.
His name was Leo Selker that became the associate provost at the University of Chicago, Illinois.
We had another.
Gerald Boe, who became the executive director of NACLS, which is the professional organization.
NACLS, and I can't tell you what that is.
It's a medical technology.
N-A-K-O-L?
N-A-C-L-E-S, NACLS.
National Association of, and I can't tell you what it is.
We had a woman who became one of the vice presidents of Herman Hospital.
There were several really good.
Bill Thompson is at Baylor College of Medicine now in the Department of Community Medicine.
Just a large number of them that did well.
And these people were coming geographically from the South?
From all over.
From all over.
Buffalo, New York, Arizona, Oklahoma.
Not every state in the Union, but there was, we had a, and not many local.
And who were your allies as you were trying to build this health program in the department?
Who were your allies?
In the university, there were no enemies.
I mean, nearly every place I went, I got help.
I wasn't used to that.
I've always been singularly impressed about that, about this institution.
It's so easy to build collaborations, or has been until just recent years anyway.
Don Clark probably helped me more than anyone because he was associate dean for research in the college.
He was my number one person I turned to when I needed help.
But we had a collaboration with Baylor College of Medicine at that time and the folks down there were helpful also.
The Department of Community Medicine then, they had a program in allied health that actually got the seminal grant in which I was assigned to.
At the same time that was going on, Robert Hurley was coordinator of health education and he was building an undergraduate degree in health.
We didn't have that.
And he and I were sharing an office so we would bounce ideas back and forth and within a year,
We had that approved by the coordinating board, and that changed things entirely as far as life as a health educator was concerned.
It wasn't long until we had 150 majors, and then that went up to about 300 undergraduate majors.
So it built pretty quickly.
And was this in the 70s?
This would be 74, roughly 74, 73 or 74.
Let's see this.
No, 73, that was approved.
Very good.
Was there then a true health science major in the department pretty soon, undergraduate?
Yes, yes.
We got the undergraduate degree first, which is kind of unusual in health.
It has been in reverse before.
We got the master's and PhD probably in 1978, somewhere along in there.
But that meant then that we would have health educators
majoring in health, and physical educators majoring in physical education.
And then there were some crossover.
Some of the physical educators would take some health classes.
What other institutions in the Southwest were offering a similar, making similar effort at that point?
We were among the first.
In the Southwest, I don't think there was a single school.
No one had a pure degree.
There were some that had a...
a program that was singled off of physical education, but I think we were the first ones.
I can't think of it.
Did you have a school somewhere else that was your model?
Tennessee was my model.
They had that kind of program.
Utah was Hurley's model.
There were others, but most of them were in the west and the northeast.
As this enrollment grew, were you able to bring in new faculty?
We were.
Of course, those were the growing days of faculty.
We were bringing in one or two faculty every year almost.
But when I got here, there were three faculty in health.
There's Robert and me and Gail Smith, who was a lecturer working on a doctorate.
And we have 10 or 11 there now, I think.
Physical education had, well, they had one, two, three, four, five, six, seven, eight, and one of those was the department head.
And I don't know what the head count over there is now.
It's considerably different.
All right, and as the semesters went on, you started having a heavier teaching load and a heavier leadership responsibility.
Did you have any particular title
Were you the...
I was the coordinator of Allied Health.
Coordinator of Allied Health.
That was a departmental title.
No one else on campus recognized it, but that's where we distinguished it.
And what are some of the other courses you began to teach?
I continued to teach the methodology class.
I began to teach research methods then.
And I taught a measurement and evaluation class.
And I taught an Allied Health
seminar for Allied Health graduates.
And I began to get a lot of 691s, a lot of dissertations.
In fact, at one time, the Allied Health people were the only health folks at the doctoral level.
And I suddenly realized I was carrying a pretty heavy load there.
And so, like all good faculty, I went in to ask for some relief.
And Carl gave me some relief, particularly in the summertime.
He helped me a little bit.
Describe some of your learning experiences as a new thesis and dissertation director at AMU.
Of course, we have the model here that you become a co-chair and then you chair a committee.
Well, my first job was to co-chair with Carl Landis.
And unfortunately, we had this first Allied Health student who was a little bit of a mismatch anyway.
And I pretty quickly learned that co-chair didn't mean co-pilot.
No, it didn't mean co-chair, but it meant co-pilot.
And so I'm sure I was frustrated some part of that time because I felt like that I knew how to do that.
And my ideas were a little different than what Carl's ideas were.
But in retrospect, I think it's a good thing, especially the steps you have to go through in order to keep the student out of trouble.
I think it was good.
Of course, George Coonsey played an important role in that time.
I don't know whether this ought to be on the tape or not, but I think we lost something when we lost George Coonsey.
Oh, no.
See, those are the kind of things we do want to know.
Why did you think so highly?
What was good about his?
What I liked was what some people didn't like.
He expected everyone to adhere to a certain standard.
And when you didn't adhere to that standard, then he bucked it back to you.
And you had to get it in shape before it came back to it.
Well, it seems now that just almost anything goes.
Before we did final defenses, we had to have the thing on blue line.
Now it's a rough draft that I look at often when I go to a final defense and more rough than anything else.
And he didn't pull punches.
He didn't mind looking you in the eye and telling you this is what he thought.
And I like that guy.
He saved me an awful lot when I was department head, but he helped me an awful lot when I was a faculty member too.
As the 70s are moving along, did you and your colleagues feel like progress was being made?
Oh, yeah.
I thought, in a lot of ways, the 70s were the Camelot years for us.
When I came here, I was taken by how much obvious devotion there was between faculty and students.
Students often would praise a faculty member and talk about,
how they felt about them.
And former students would talk about how much they actually loved some of their faculty.
And faculty, when they talked about students, would do likewise.
In fact, more than once I'd go in the office and one that I remember best was Homer Tolson that we talked about earlier.
He had a needlepoint on his wall that said, students come first in this office always.
And he meant that.
If I came in as a faculty member and he had a student and I tried to interrupt that
He let me know very quickly that he wasn't available right then.
In a lot of ways, I thought we met our mission in those years as well as we ever have.
But yes, no question, we were making headway.
We were being hamstrung to some degree by the growth of the place.
We were always behind the curve in terms of facilities and those kind of things.
Now, did you ever in those early years have any male-female situations in class where the...
where the Aggie male didn't want the Aggie female there?
I never did.
I never did.
I know it happened some in the Corps.
I know we had some difficulty in integrating the band with women.
But I never did in our department.
In fact, I can remember as department head getting an enrollment report one time, and this was like the mid-'80s.
And I looked at it and I said, Linda, Linda was my secretary, we've got more women than we have men in this department.
She says, no, we don't.
We counted up, and we were 10 or 15 more women than men.
And that slipped up on us.
I didn't realize it happened.
I don't think we had any problem with that, certainly not in classrooms.
What about ethnic diversity?
It wasn't very much then.
It wasn't very much ethnic diversity then.
But do you remember any problems with Hispanic students?
I didn't remember any.
I think what happened occurred out in the
and then formal settings.
Of course, in our classes, in our physical education activity classes, that's where integration occurred best because everyone was equal there and the best skilled one got the ball the most.
In the classrooms, I didn't see any sign of it.
But we just, in our field,
It's kind of a unique thing about ethnic diversity.
We didn't have many minorities who came into our field because they were good enough to go to college.
They often elected a business or liberal arts often, and they didn't just elect our program.
Even though most people on campus thought that most of the athletes came to our department, that wasn't true for the most part.
We had to recruit.
blacks to get them in our faculty.
We had to actually work at getting that and I was I'm kind of proud of the fact that I hired the first one and that's after I became department head.
All right now we'll want to work that in a little bit.
In those early years do you remember any realities with athletes in class?
You don't have to name names.
